<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-647-572  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 647 572.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 12 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer Sciences makes friends in Washington. (Washington D.C.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John; Endrijonas, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Computer Sciences Corp. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    CSC.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Aviation AdministrationUnited States. ArmyGovernment ContractsSoftware packagesProduct DevelopmentAir Traffic ControlLogisticsDefense Contracts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>COMPUTER SCIENCES MAKES FRIENDS IN WASHINGTON MOORESTOWN, NEW JERSEY, U.S.A.,andO;1989 SEP 1 (NB) -- Computer Sciences Corporation is close to winning a newdefense department software contract and has just won a big contract with theFederal Aviation Administration.andP;  The Army has designated Computer Sciencesas the winner of the design competition phase for an integrated systemintended to speed acquisition of new weapon systems.andP;  The contract will beworth several hundred million dollars to the company that wins the finalgo-ahead.andP;  The proposed system, called the Computer-aided Acquisition andLogistics Support or CALS system, will also serve as a central clearingsystem to aid in the maintenance of weapons.andP;  Computer Sciences has alsosigned a $134 million contract with IBM to provide software and relatedservices to upgrade and modernize the US air traffic control system.andP;  IBM isthe Federal Aviation Administration's (FAA) primary contractor for the $3.6billion program known as Advanced Automation System.andP;  CSC's contract spans a13 year period backdated to November 1988 (CSC spokesman Jim Furlongexplained to Newsbytes that CSC was able to begin work on the project whilethe contract was in negotiation).andP;  Proposed additional work during the13-years-plus anticipated options for support through the year 2010 couldraise the total value of CSC's contract to $700 million.andP;  CSC'sresponsibilities include the development of applications and support softwareand the test, evaluation, installation and integration of software at factoryand FAA sites.andP;  The software will be written in Ada, the government-sponsoredstandard programming language.andP;  (John McCormick andamp; JanetEndrijonas/19890908/Press Contact: Jim Furlong or Bruce Plowman, CSC,213-615-0311)</TEXT></DOC>